The Akashas suffered a major blow yesterday after a judge said she had no power to order production of extradited brothers.Judge Dora Chepkwony dismissed an application by family lawyer Cliff Ombeta. The family wanted the court to issue orders compelling the police to produce the two brothers in court.Chepkwony said the applicant failed to disclose the whereabouts of the subjects.Baktash Akasha, Ibrahim Akasha, Gulam Hussein and Vijaygiri Goswami were fighting extradition to the US, but were grabbed from different venues in January and flown to the US. They face drug trafficking charges.&ldquo;In law, a person has a right to seek a habeas corpus but in this case, the matter has been overtaken by events,&rdquo; she said.Chepkwony also advised the applicants to file a constitutional application for redress.Ombeta argued his clients have been held in communicado, terming it an abuse of their basic human rights.Inspector General Joseph Boinnet and Director of Criminal Investigations Ndegwa Muhoro were summoned in court to produce the two. They were to appear in court on January 30.